 strategy of appropriation at the interface between literary economics, law, and theoretical discourses of literature. She investigates the complex expectations surrounding the strong link between an individual author subject and its alienable text, a link that several postmodern writers powerfully question and violate. Identifying three distinct practices of postmodern plagiarism, the book examines their specific situatedness, precepts, and subversive potential as litmus tests for the literary market, and the ongoing dynamic notion of the concepts authorship, originality, and creativity.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aImitation in literature. 0aPlagiarismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPlagiarismzUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 4aAutorschaft. 4aGeistiges Eigentum. 4aLiterarischer Markt. 4aPlagiat. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aAuthorship.  aIntellectual Property.  aLiterary Market.  aPlagiarism.  aPostmodern Literature.  aSubversion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2015 Part 1z978311076251808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2015z9783110438673oZDB-23-DKU0 cEPUBz97831103942690 cprintz978311037895540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311037910540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110379105423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110379105/original  a978-3-11-07009